Can a Machine-Based Sommelier predict exceptional wine?¶

Using 150,000 wine reviews, can we predict a 90+ point wine?

Examples of potential uses:

  1. Prioritizing of wine production
  2. Purchasing decisions
  3. Determining changing wine preferences over time

Data¶

The wine review data used for point predictions is sourced from Kaggle's "Wine Review Data" set located here

The data was scraped from Wine Enthusiast on November 22nd, 2017. As a guide for the points system, Wine Spectator magazine, one of the largest wine scoring operations, indicates the following qualitative rating by score*:

  • 60-69. Wines are flawed and not recommended
  • 70-79 Wines are flawed and taste average
  • 80-84 wines are above average to good
  • 85-90 wines are good to very good
  • 90-94 wines are superior to exceptional
  • 95-100. Wines are benchmark examples or classic

*The data is only comprised of wines with ratings of 80 and above

Goals¶

  1. Train a classifier to determine whether or not a bottle of wine is exceptional (90+).
  2. Understand what makes a wine exceptional (feature exploration).
  3. Explore whether or not we can go further than a classifier, and instead use a regressor to predict points.

Approach¶

  1. Visualizing and quantifying relationships in the data to better understand common point values, prices, varieties, and countries and/or regions. This will also help inform whether or not 90 is an appropriate cutoff point
  2. Preprocessing text-based features by introducing metadata features. Additionally, we will utilize a natural language processing technique known as Term frequency inverse document frequency (TF-IDF) to extract the words that best summarize the descriptions
  3. Exploring several classifiers including Naive Bayes, Logistic Regression,Gradient Boost, Random Forest, and a voting ensemle of all four.
  4. Testing whether or not automated feature selection of PCA is helpful in increasing performance and/or generalizability of the model.
  5. Testing which classifier hyperparameters help best to achieve increased performance and/or generalizability of the model.
  6. Testing how the model performs when removing key features such as price.
  7. Testing linear regression to determine a baseline for regressor performance.

Steps¶

  1. Load the data
  2. Visualize by country, variety, price, and point assignment
  3. Add features for text
  4. Test Classifiers: Naive Bayes, Logistic Regression, Random Forest, and voting ensemble of all three
  5. Analyze important features
  6. Model selection
  7. Conclusion & Future steps

Step 1: Load the data¶

There are 150,930 reviews in the Wine Enthusiast data set. Since 90+ wines are considered "superior to exceptional", I added a flag to indicate wines with a 90+ rating. Also, I filled in the mean price for wines where price was missing (13,695 or 9%).

Step 2: Visualize by country, variety, price, and point assignment¶

  • Wine in this dataset is dominated by about 10 countries, where conditions are favorable for grapes
  • Chardonnay, Pinot Noir, Cabernet Sauvignon, and a Red Blend are the most popular wine varieties
  • The highest priced wine in the dataset is a \$2,300 Bordeaux-style Red Blend (99 points), while the lowest priced wine is a \$4 Merlot (86 points). The average price of a bottle of wine in the dataset was \$33
  • There is a positively correlated relationship between price and points of .44.
  • The average point value assigned is 88, and approximately 68% of the wine bottles are rated below 90

Step 3: Add features for text¶

The description column offers a few sentences about the wine. I used this to create several new features such as:

  • Word count
  • Character count
  • Average number of words
  • Number of stop words (commonly used word (such as "the" to ignore based on the english dictionary)
  • Number of numbers
  • Number of percents

I then created dummy variables for the remaining columns (excluding description). I also added designation and winery to the description since there were many variations and this created tens of thousands of new dummy variables, and thus memory errors.

Finally, I used a TFIDF vectorizer on the newly created description column (that now includes winery and designation) to take the top 1,000 words from the description and create columns for each word.

In [29]:
#avg word function
def avg_word(sentence):
  words = sentence.split()
  return (sum(len(word) for word in words)/len(words))
In [30]:
##Add feaures

#text features
stop = stopwords.words('english')

df['word_count'] = df['description'].apply(lambda x: len(str(x).split(" ")))
df['char_count'] = df['description'].str.len() ## this also includes spaces
df['avg_word'] = df['description'].apply(lambda x: avg_word(x))
df['stopwords'] = df['description'].apply(lambda x: len([x for x in x.split() if x in stop]))
df['numerics'] = df['description'].apply(lambda x: len([x for x in x.split() if x.isdigit()]))
df['percent'] = df['description'].apply(lambda x: len([x for x in x.split() if x.endswith('%')]))

#description processing
df['description'] = df['description'].apply(lambda x: " ".join(x.lower() for x in x.split()))
df['description'] = df['description'].str.replace('[^\w\s]','')
df['description'] = df['description'].apply(lambda x: " ".join(x for x in x.split() if x not in stop))

#Create tfidf features
#TF-IDF:  NLP technicque that is intended to reflect how important a word is to the description
#in the collection of all descriptions.  Here, we take the top 1,000 top words
tfidf = TfidfVectorizer(max_features=1000, lowercase=True, analyzer='word',
stop_words= 'english',ngram_range=(1,1))
vect = tfidf.fit_transform(df_description['description'])

columns = tfidf.get_feature_names()

a = vect.toarray()

df2 = pd.DataFrame(np.reshape(a, (len(a),vect.shape[1])),columns=columns)
df = pd.concat([df, df2],axis=1)

Step 4: Test classifiers¶

I tested 4 classifiers and a voting ensemble of the 4 in order to determine which would produce the higest f1 score. The f1-score is useful since it considers both the precision and recall. Precision, in this case, would be the percentage of exceptional wines predicted that were actually exceptional, while recall is the percentage of exceptional predications that were actually correct.

While the highest f1-score on the test set is most important, it's also important to consider the results on the training set to determine if the model is perhaps overfitting or not generalized enough. An ideal model, therefore, would have a high f1-score with little difference between the training and test set.

Attempting feature selection and PCA¶

Since the random forest performed best on the test set, I attempted feature selection and PCA to see if I could build a more generalizable model where the f1-score for the training set and test set would converge. I started with feature selection and PCA of 100, 250, 500, and 1000. This had the effect of lowering the f1-score for both the training and test set.

Attempting PCA without feature selection¶

I then attempted PCA without feature selection for 2000 and 3000 components. Once again, this reduced the f1-score slightly for the training set, and did not improve the f1-score for the test set. As a result, I concluded that feature selection and PCA would not be useful for increasing model performance and generalizability.

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Since a random forest without feature selection and PCA seems to perform best, I decided to tune the hyperparameters of the random forest classifier to improve performance using RandomizedSearchCV.

In [49]:
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
# Number of trees in random forest
n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 200, stop = 2000, num = 10)]
# Number of features to consider at every split
max_features = ['auto', 'sqrt']
# Maximum number of levels in tree
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 110, num = 11)]
max_depth.append(None)
# Minimum number of samples required to split a node
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]
# Minimum number of samples required at each leaf node
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]
# Method of selecting samples for training each tree
bootstrap = [True, False]
# Create the random grid
random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'max_features': max_features,
               'max_depth': max_depth,
               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
               'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf,
               'bootstrap': bootstrap}
print(random_grid)

# Fit the random search model
rf_random.fit(X_train, y_train)

#Try a Voting Ensemble - Naive Bayes, Logistic Regression, Random Forest with feature selection and PCA
#split data
# Definine outcome and predictors.

start_time = time.time()

#Set pickle file name
rf_filename = r'ensemble_4_models.pkl'

#pickle the pipeline
if not os.path.exists(rf_filename):
    # Initialize and fit the model.
    clf1 =  ensemble.RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100)
    clf2 =  LogisticRegression(C=1e9)
    clf3 =  BernoulliNB()
    
    params = {'n_estimators': 100,
          'max_depth': 4,
          'loss': 'deviance',
           'learning_rate': .99}
    
    # Initialize and fit the model.
    clf4 = ensemble.GradientBoostingClassifier(**params)
    
    
    eclf1 = ensemble.VotingClassifier(estimators=[('rf', clf1), ('lr', clf2), ('bnb', clf3), ('gb', clf4)], voting='soft', weights=[1.2,1,1,1])
    scaler =  StandardScaler()
    sklearn_pca = PCA(n_components=1000)

    pipeline = Pipeline([
        ('scale', scaler),
        #('feature_selection', SelectFromModel(LinearSVC(loss='l2', penalty='l1', dual=False))),
        #('dimensions', sklearn_pca),
        ('classifier', eclf1)
    ])
    pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)
    pickle.dump(pipeline, open(rf_filename, 'wb'))
else:
    pipeline = pickle.load(open(rf_filename, 'rb'))

print('Voting Ensemble - Random Forest, Logistic Regression, Gradient Boost, and Naive Bayes')
print('Training set:')
print(classification_report(y_train, pipeline.predict(X_train)))
print('Test set:')
print(classification_report(y_test, pipeline.predict(X_test)))
print('Accuracy:  {}'.format(accuracy_score(y_test, pipeline.predict(X_test))))
print("--- %s seconds ---" % (time.time() - start_time))

Model Selection¶

As a result, the Random Forest model was selected due to it's high f1-score of .91. While the model may be overfit on the training set (with an f1-score of 1.00), no other model or combination exceeded .89.

Step 5: Analyze Important Features¶

By looking at the top coefficients from the logistic regression results, some of the key features/words contributing to an exceptional classification include:

  • Character count
  • Price
  • Mendoza region
  • Ctes de Provence
  • The word "sample"
  • The word "rich"
  • The word "beautiful"
  • The word "complex"

On the flip side, some of the negative features/words that contributed to a wine not being classified as exceptional include:

  • Mendoza province
  • The country of Argentina
  • The province of Provence
  • The country of France
  • The province of Southwest France
  • The region of Bourgogne

Additionally, important features may be revealed by investigating the feature_importances from the random forest classifier. Feature importance is defined as the total decrease in node impurity (weighted by the probability of reaching that node (which is approximated by the proportion of samples reaching that node) averaged over all trees of the ensemble. The top features include:

  • Price
  • Character count
  • word count
  • average word size
  • Number of stop words
  • The word "complex"
  • The word "years"
  • The word "rich"
